1.5  The Emergency Response Program

The Emergency Response Program is divided into two elements, as only properly trained and qualified personnel are authorized to respond to emergencies.  Personnel that are not trained to OSHA 1910.120 (q) standards notify and evacuate.  Only the responding Fire Department(s) and 6th Street Cooling?s 1910.120 (q) trained personnel would respond to an actual emergency.  Emergency response equipment is maintained on-site.  

The facility maintains required written emergency planning documents.  Written ammonia emergency action procedures are detailed in the 6th Street Cooling, LLC ?Integrated Contingency Plan? (ICP).  The Hazardous Material Business Plan and the Emergency Action Plan detail procedures for non-responding personnel.  The Hazardous Material Business Plan contains procedures for small spills and procedures for materials other than ammonia.  Each of these Plans are maintained on-site and updated on a regular basis.

